massive packet of biscuits” and “three different-coloured peppers in a bag”?</p> <p><strong>What? </strong>Perhaps this will refresh your memory: “Notes are dispensed below the scanner”; “Remove this item before continuing”; or even …</p> <p><strong>No! Please! </strong>“Unexpected item in bagging area.”</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MI1Lr08LDps\"                                                                        > <iframe width=\"460\" height=\"259\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/MI1Lr08LDps?wmode=opaque&feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen></iframe> <figcaption>Tesco self-checkout machines to have new, male, voice. Source: Tesco PLC</figcaption> </figure>   <p><strong>Oh God. It’s Britain’s national cliche.</strong> Don’t be so mean. For six years, <a href=\"http://www.voiceovers.co.uk/helena.breck\">Breck’s voice</a> has charmed shoppers at the automatic tills at Tesco, Asda, Sainsbury’s and Marks &amp; Spencer with its bright yet classy explanations of how to do very basic things we’ve all done hundreds of times before and are probably redundant anyway because the machine isn’t working, but which we’re forced to listen to over and over again while we wait for a member of staff with a gilet and a key to please, God, make it go away.</p> <p><strong>That’s kind of what I meant.</strong> Anyway, now Tesco has made her go away.</p> <p><strong>How come?</strong> <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/epic/tsco/11772689/Tesco-replaces-irritating-unexpected-item-in-the-bagging-area-self-checkout-voice-with-male-recording.html\">They’ve replaced her</a> with a slightly more laconic man.</p> <p><strong>Which old soap operas was he in?</strong> I’ll have to get back to you on that.</p> <p><strong>Didn’t the machines’ American manufacturer, NCR, say that it had researched the subject and found that customers </strong><a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/10950089/Woman-behind-unexpected-item-in-bagging-area-message-revealed.html\"><strong>overwhelmingly responded better to the female voice</strong></a><strong>?</strong> Why, yes, it did. Maybe that was before people had heard the voice 60,000 times.</p> <p><strong>So, what is this new man like?</strong> Oh, you know: resonant, posh-ish, improbably excited by the minutiae of shopping. Instead of Breck’s rather cold way of saying, “Notes are dispensed below the scanner,” he gives us a chummy, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MI1Lr08LDps\">“Don’t forget your change, especially notes!”</a></p> <p><strong>He has a point. No one wants to forget those lovely notes.</strong> No, indeed. Or to be repeatedly told about it.</p> <p><strong>Still, I don’t see how anyone could match the quality of Breck’s “Beep!” when the barcode hits the laser.</strong> I don’t think that was her.</p> <p><strong>Do say: </strong>“Please take your items.”</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> “Please unplug yourself.”</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10637632","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-08-03T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2347074","internalContentCode":"457638399","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"Britain’s biggest supermarket has had it up to here with unexpected items, and former EastEnders actor Helena Breck has paid the price: her self-service voiceovers have been replaced by those of a cheery, posh gent","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Voice over: why Tesco’s female tills have checked out for the final time","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-08-02T18:00:01.596+01:00","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/31/1438350431437/b4040084-94c8-41c3-b019-f0ecc90d11d1-140x84.jpeg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"55bb7aebe4b08e990d44da75","newspaperPageNumber":"3","commentCloseDate":"2015-08-05T17:00:01Z","stan