reatures Great and Small.</p> <p><strong>Age: </strong>45. The first book was published in 1970. The TV series came eight years later.</p> <p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Souped-up. Refitted. Buffed to a high shine. Made over. Smoothed, glossed, planed and varnished. Altogether Americanised. Potentially.</p> <p><strong>A glamorous Darrowby? Are you sure? </strong>Well, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/jul/27/hbo-all-creatures-great-and-small-remake-bbc\" title=\"\">rumours are rife</a> that HBO – home of Sex and the City, Game of Thrones, The Wire and Trues Blood and Detective – has picked up the rights to the BBC drama and wants to give it a big-budget remake.</p> <p><strong>Umm … I’m going to need a moment.</strong> By all means, my friend, take it. I understand.</p> <p><strong>We’re talking about the one in the 80s? The gentle adventures of Christopher Timothy as James Herriot, the 1950s rural Yorkshire vet? </strong>Yes, that’s the one. Robert Hardy – a ham so rare it can’t be cured – as his cantankerous boss Siegfried, Carol Drinkwater then Lynda Bellingham as his lovely wife and Peter Davison as Siegfried’s younger brother Tristan. The very same.</p> <p><strong>So, what’s gone on with the world that this has come to pass? </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jul/12/doctor-who-bbc-worldwide\" title=\"\">Doctor Who</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jul/16/uk-period-drama-scores-emmy-nominee-success-with-downton-and-wolf-hall\" title=\"\">Downton Abbey</a> and <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-3139959/It-s-Smouldark-BBC-drama-premieres-sparks-outpouring-lustful-tweets-aimed-star-Aidan-Turner.html\" title=\"\">Poldark</a>, basically. They’ve done spectacularly well in the US, so the net is being cast ever wider.</p> <p><strong>I wonder how they pitched it.</strong> Downton Abbey with pigs? Poldark with shorter hair? Doctor Who with absolutely nothing resembling any bit of anything about Doctor Who, except for Peter Davison, who isn’t remotely the Doctor Who you know and love?</p> <p><strong>Any word on who’s in the casting frame? </strong>Pure speculation at this point. But who wouldn’t love to see Chris Noth as Siegfried, Matthew McConaughey as James Herriot and Lena Headey as Mrs H? And the postwar Yorkshire Dales as a microfarm in the Obamas’ vegetable garden? And Nicholas Cage as the sheepdog being put down every other episode? Who wouldn’t? <em>Who wouldn’t?</em></p> <p><strong>How are they going to find anyone method enough to put his arm up a cow’s bum 18 times a series? </strong>Christian Bale for the arm, Dustin Hoffman for the bum. Sorted.</p> <p><strong>Do say:</strong> This’ll play in Peoria.</p> <p><strong>Don’t say:</strong> Maybe the Brontës can come visit! SJP as Charlotte, Kim Cattrall as Emily and Cynthia Nixon as Anne! Awesome! Let’s roll!</p>","internalOctopusCode":"10624205","productionOffice":"UK","newspaperEditionDate":"2015-07-28T00:00:00Z","hasStoryPackage":"false","internalPageCode":"2344332","internalContentCode":"457598665","publication":"The Guardian","trailText":"After the stateside success of British dramas such as Poldark, Doctor Who and Downton Abbey, the home of Game of Thrones and True Detective is rumoured to be planning a remake of the Sunday tea-time veterinary drama","allowUgc":"false","headline":"Downton Abbey with pigs? Why an HBO version of All Creatures Great and Small isn’t completely daft  \r\n","isInappropriateForSponsorship":"false","byline":"The Guardian","commentable":"true","firstPublicationDate":"2015-07-27T15:49:51.610+01:00","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2015/7/27/1438007435881/18346e24-f037-4862-88d1-b11ffc875347-140x84.jpeg","isPremoderated":"false","internalComposerCode":"55b631ede4b0221a8b9d316c","newspaperPageNumber":"3","commentCloseDate":"2015-07-30T15:45:00+01:00","standfirst":"After the stateside success of British dramas such as Poldark, Doctor 